Introduction

The purpose of this report is to highlight my methods in developing a spatial regression model of average annual energy use at the census block group level with various structural and sociodemographic explanatory variables.

First, I load in the required R packages for the analysis:

Data Clean-Up

cbg <- readOGR("Energy_Burden/Metro_EnergyBurden_11817.shp")
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "Energy_Burden/Metro_EnergyBurden_11817.shp", layer: "Metro_EnergyBurden_11817"
## with 978 features
## It has 46 fields
#Calculate density and remove the lowest density block groups
cbg$cbg_area <- sapply(slot(cbg, "polygons"), slot, "area") #Create an area column
cbg <- subset(cbg, cbg$cbg_area < 5.0e+07 & cbg$cbg_area > 1e+06) #visually removed the large and very small block groups
cbg <- subset(cbg, cbg$sfr_nt > 40) # Subset CBGs with less than 40 SFR (As Chang et al did)
cbg <- subset(cbg, cbg$TOTexp15 > 600 & cbg$TOTexp15 < 2000)

#Impute Medians
# There Shouldn't be many NA's
medePuter <- function(x){
  x<-as.numeric(as.character(x)) #first convert each column into numeric if it is from factor
  x[is.na(x)] =median(x, na.rm=TRUE) #convert the item with NA to median value from the column
  x #display the column
}

cbg@data <- as.data.frame(apply(cbg@data,2,medePuter)) #Imputes medians for all of the missing independent variables

cbg <- subset(cbg, cbg$yearbuilt > 1800) #Anything with an average age of 1800 or older probably isn't accurate..

OLS Results:

Spatial Regression

Spatial Weights: Creating a weights matrix with K-Nearest Neighbors and 5 neighbors to create a matrix from census block group centroids:

tl_point<-gCentroid(cbg_redu,byid=T)

nb <-  knn2nb(knearneigh(tl_point, k = 5))

nb_lines<-spTransform(nb2lines(nb, proj4string = cbg_redu@proj4string, coords = coordinates(tl_point)), CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84"))
leaflet() %>% addProviderTiles(providers$OpenStreetMap) %>%
  addCircleMarkers(data=spTransform(tl_point,CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84"))
                   ,weight=2
                   ,color="black"
                   ,fillColor = "grey"
                   ,fillOpacity = 0.15
                   ,opacity= 1
                   ,radius=4) %>%
  addPolylines(data=nb_lines,color="red",weight=2)

Assessing the correlation between each observations residual and the mean value of its neighbors residuals. There appears to be a positive spatial trend:

#Creating Spatial lag and plotting
cbg_redu$resid <- sfmod.redu$residuals
resnb <- sapply(nb, function(x) mean(sfmod.redu$residuals[x]))
plot(sfmod.redu$residuals, resnb, xlab ='Residuals', ylab = 'Mean of adjacent residuals')
text(-150,150,paste0("Correlation: ", round(cor(cbg_redu$resid, resnb), 4)), col="red")

Testing spatial autocorrelation of the OLS residuals:

weights <- nb2listw(nb)
moran.mc(cbg_redu$resid, weights, 999) 
## 
##  Monte-Carlo simulation of Moran I
## 
## data:  cbg_redu$resid 
## weights: weights  
## number of simulations + 1: 1000 
## 
## statistic = 0.22095, observed rank = 1000, p-value = 0.001
## alternative hypothesis: greater
moran.plot(cbg_redu$resid, weights, main = "Moran's Plot", xlab = "Residuals", ylab = "Spatially Lagged Residuals")

The residuals of the reduced OLS model are spatially autocorrelated, suggesting that a spatial regression model is necessary. Now we need to determine whether a spatial error or lag model would be more appropriate:

lm.LMtests(sfmod.redu, listw=weights)
## 
##  Lagrange multiplier diagnostics for spatial dependence
## 
## data:  
## model: lm(formula = TOTexp15 ~ +I(2017 - yearbuilt) + log_bldgsqft
## + Avg_HHSize + MHI + log_Black + log_Over65 + log_acres +
## log_mfrn, data = cbg_redu)
## weights: weights
## 
## LMErr = 93.45, df = 1, p-value < 0.00000000000000022

The last line in these results indicates that the Spatial Error Model is most appropriate (p < 0.0001)

Spatial Error Model

Calculating a spatial error regression model based off of the reduced OLS model:

sem <- errorsarlm(TOTexp15~
                 + I(2017 - yearbuilt)
                 + log_bldgsqft
                 + Avg_HHSize
                 + MHI
                 + log_Black
                 + log_Over65
                 + log_acres
                 + log_mfrn, data= cbg_redu, weights)
summary(sem)

Normality in Residuals:

## Testing Normality in Residuals
shapiro.test(sem$residuals) #indicates residuals are not normaly distributed.
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  sem$residuals
## W = 0.99299, p-value = 0.002368
#Check Qnorm
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(sem$residuals, breaks=20, main = "Spatial Error Model - Residuals", xlab = "Residuals", freq = F)
qqnorm(sem$residuals)

Assessing Heteroskedasticity:

There could be a slight relationship between the fitted values and residuals:

plot(sem$residuals~sem$fitted.values, main = "Fitted Values vs. Residuals", xlab = "Fitted (Estimated) Total Expenditure", ylab = "Residuals", pch = 19)

Assessing Spatial Autocorrelation of the Residuals:

Results indicate that there is no significant spatial autocorrelation of the spatial error model residuals (p-value ~0.84):

# Spatial autocorrelation of residuals
moran.mc(sem$residuals, weights, 999)
## 
##  Monte-Carlo simulation of Moran I
## 
## data:  sem$residuals 
## weights: weights  
## number of simulations + 1: 1000 
## 
## statistic = -0.03419, observed rank = 61, p-value = 0.939
## alternative hypothesis: greater
moran.plot(sem$residuals, weights, main = "Moran's Plot for SEM", xlab = "SEM Residuals", ylab = "Spatially Lagged SEM Residuals")
